{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/how-many-positions-on-a-rubiks-cube/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Chris Hunt"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"c3fa04b2-4285-54fc-a97e-ca04b58720c2","excerpt":"The Rubik’s Cube is a challenging puzzle to solve, largely because there are so\nmany positions. Wouldn’t it be fun to know exactly how many positions there\nare…","html":"<p class=\"py-4\">The Rubik’s Cube is a challenging puzzle to solve, largely because there are so\nmany positions. Wouldn’t it be fun to know exactly how many positions there\nare? Wouldn’t it be even <em>more</em> fun to know how to calculate that number for\nyourself?</p>\n<h2 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-4xl\">Back To The Basics</h2>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Imagine we have three marbles and each marble is a different color. One is red,\nanother is green, and the third is blue. If we were to place the marbles in a\nrow on the table in front of us, how would we arrange them?</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 622px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d610f9b8b65599aee13b85d2fa35e7e8/604ec/m1h89fwdupk1a_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 31.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"01-marbles.png\"\n        title=\"01-marbles.png\"\n        src=\"/static/d610f9b8b65599aee13b85d2fa35e7e8/604ec/m1h89fwdupk1a_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d610f9b8b65599aee13b85d2fa35e7e8/772e8/m1h89fwdupk1a_small.png 200w,\n/static/d610f9b8b65599aee13b85d2fa35e7e8/e17e5/m1h89fwdupk1a_small.png 400w,\n/static/d610f9b8b65599aee13b85d2fa35e7e8/604ec/m1h89fwdupk1a_small.png 622w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 622px) 100vw, 622px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">The ordering that we’ve selected is just one possible position of many. We\nmight have chosen to put green first instead of red. Each of these positions is\na <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation\" class=\"text-blue-700\"><em>permutation</em></a> of our marbles. If\nwe were to rearrange the marbles, then we would find another permutation.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"p-4 my-4 bg-orange-200 border-l-4 border-orange-500 italic\">\n<p class=\"py-4\">“A <strong>permutation</strong> of a set of objects is an arrangement of those objects\ninto a particular order.” - wikipedia</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"py-4\">In order to count how many positions we have for the Rubik’s Cube, we will\nfirst learn how to count permutations for our set of marbles.</p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Counting Permutations</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We intuitively know that our set of three marbles has several different\npermutations, but exactly how many are there? One way to count is to rearrange\nthe marbles on a table until we’ve found each permutation. Doing this, we can\nsee that we have <strong>six permutations</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/cb755f60af6047657f7e2637da7aa669/a6d36/dwxeb8d4xfcc4g_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"02-marbles.png\"\n        title=\"02-marbles.png\"\n        src=\"/static/cb755f60af6047657f7e2637da7aa669/a6d36/dwxeb8d4xfcc4g_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/cb755f60af6047657f7e2637da7aa669/772e8/dwxeb8d4xfcc4g_small.png 200w,\n/static/cb755f60af6047657f7e2637da7aa669/e17e5/dwxeb8d4xfcc4g_small.png 400w,\n/static/cb755f60af6047657f7e2637da7aa669/a6d36/dwxeb8d4xfcc4g_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">When We’ve Lost Our Marbles</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Visualizing each permutation works well when we only have three marbles, but\nwhat if we wanted to count permutations for a bag of 500 marbles? We’ll need a\ndifferent strategy.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">There’s a nice mathematical trick we can use for counting permutations called\nthe <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial\" class=\"text-blue-700\"><em>factorial</em></a>. Given <em>n</em> items, the\nfactorial of <em>n</em> is equal to the number of permutations of <em>n</em>.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"p-4 my-4 bg-orange-200 border-l-4 border-orange-500 italic\">\n<p class=\"py-4\">“The <strong>factorial</strong> of a non-negative integer n, denoted by n!, is the product\nof all positive integers less than or equal to n.” - wikipedia</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Since we have three marbles, we can calculate the total number of permutations\nby calculating <strong>three factorial</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1ffbbd5b4c4c7fc0fbad989a50ec081f/a6d36/6akljtu8szh3g_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 11.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAACCAIAAADXZGvcAAAACXBIWXMAAAsSAAALEgHS3X78AAAAf0lEQVQI1x3L4QtDQBzGcf//f6P2BiUx6VxRx47YDodNuHE3trzza/W8+PbUR+vr1Db1ZXx8ZbctfJecRO46MZicqxg7/2BK1CUNf6r7vJtje4LKSKAVt9C1L/CWFOcp2leOfLNlBPmWGArAY58HngEmiTwlqiS+vlp6z7Bj6SfSGWaxbAw7ZgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg=='); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"03-three-factorial.png\"\n        title=\"03-three-factorial.png\"\n        src=\"/static/1ffbbd5b4c4c7fc0fbad989a50ec081f/a6d36/6akljtu8szh3g_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1ffbbd5b4c4c7fc0fbad989a50ec081f/772e8/6akljtu8szh3g_small.png 200w,\n/static/1ffbbd5b4c4c7fc0fbad989a50ec081f/e17e5/6akljtu8szh3g_small.png 400w,\n/static/1ffbbd5b4c4c7fc0fbad989a50ec081f/a6d36/6akljtu8szh3g_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h2 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-4xl\">Getting Oriented</h2>\n<p class=\"py-4\">A marble does not have an orientation. It cannot be flipped or rotated. It\nalways appears the same no matter how it’s placed on the table. When we counted\nthe the number of positions for our marbles, all we cared about was their\npermutation.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">What if we wanted to calculate the total number of positions for a set of\n<strong>three playing cards</strong>?</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Initially, the problem looks the same. We have three cards and know that they\ncan be arranged in <strong>three factorial</strong> different permutations, just like the\nmarbles.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/93a8c71eff11aacad14bbcc21f3e4239/a6d36/zjj7aooizhwehq_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 48%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"04-cards.png\"\n        title=\"04-cards.png\"\n        src=\"/static/93a8c71eff11aacad14bbcc21f3e4239/a6d36/zjj7aooizhwehq_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/93a8c71eff11aacad14bbcc21f3e4239/772e8/zjj7aooizhwehq_small.png 200w,\n/static/93a8c71eff11aacad14bbcc21f3e4239/e17e5/zjj7aooizhwehq_small.png 400w,\n/static/93a8c71eff11aacad14bbcc21f3e4239/a6d36/zjj7aooizhwehq_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Playing cards, however, <em>do</em> have an orientation. We can flip any of the three\ncards and we’ll end up with a <em>different</em> position. In order to calculate the\ntotal number of positions, we’ll need to factor in <strong>both the permutation and\norientation</strong> of each card.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/f981e78dfaa5a07c1b19c8eaee0f18f3/a6d36/wxtbgbb0fa5uvw_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 48%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"05-cards.png\"\n        title=\"05-cards.png\"\n        src=\"/static/f981e78dfaa5a07c1b19c8eaee0f18f3/a6d36/wxtbgbb0fa5uvw_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f981e78dfaa5a07c1b19c8eaee0f18f3/772e8/wxtbgbb0fa5uvw_small.png 200w,\n/static/f981e78dfaa5a07c1b19c8eaee0f18f3/e17e5/wxtbgbb0fa5uvw_small.png 400w,\n/static/f981e78dfaa5a07c1b19c8eaee0f18f3/a6d36/wxtbgbb0fa5uvw_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We’ve already learned how to calculate the total number of permutations as\n<strong>three factorial</strong>. Next, we’ll see how to calculate the total number of\norientations for each position.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We have <strong>three playing cards</strong> and each card has <strong>two possible\norientations</strong>, face <em>up</em> or face <em>down</em>. For each of our <strong>three factorial\npermutations</strong>, we are able to reach all of these orientations.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 656px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/46d98cdf7fc19e733b3d325dc1047e99/748f4/f82qff73bqzatw_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54.49999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"06-all-card-permutations.png\"\n        title=\"06-all-card-permutations.png\"\n        src=\"/static/46d98cdf7fc19e733b3d325dc1047e99/748f4/f82qff73bqzatw_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/46d98cdf7fc19e733b3d325dc1047e99/772e8/f82qff73bqzatw_small.png 200w,\n/static/46d98cdf7fc19e733b3d325dc1047e99/e17e5/f82qff73bqzatw_small.png 400w,\n/static/46d98cdf7fc19e733b3d325dc1047e99/748f4/f82qff73bqzatw_small.png 656w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 656px) 100vw, 656px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">How many total orientations are there for one permutation of our set of three\ncards? We could count them using the image above, but it’s faster to calculate.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We have <strong>three playing cards</strong> and each card has <strong>two orientations</strong>. The\ntotal number of orientations for one permutation of the cards can be calculated\nas the <strong>third power of two</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/fc232be656347c9ed75552f1d21371d0/a6d36/7vqqrgkecweka_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 13%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"07-third-power-of-two.png\"\n        title=\"07-third-power-of-two.png\"\n        src=\"/static/fc232be656347c9ed75552f1d21371d0/a6d36/7vqqrgkecweka_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/fc232be656347c9ed75552f1d21371d0/772e8/7vqqrgkecweka_small.png 200w,\n/static/fc232be656347c9ed75552f1d21371d0/e17e5/7vqqrgkecweka_small.png 400w,\n/static/fc232be656347c9ed75552f1d21371d0/a6d36/7vqqrgkecweka_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Total Positions for Three Cards</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We’ve determined the total number of permutations for our cards is <strong>three\nfactorial</strong> and the total number of orientations for each of those permutations\nis the <strong>third power of two</strong>. Calculating the number of positions is done by\nmultiplying the number of permutations by the number of orientations.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 542px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/fe43118105fcf863b5d7898e9fd17c7e/c0388/pqz7dxg9lg6wa_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 20%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"08-card-total-permutations.png\"\n        title=\"08-card-total-permutations.png\"\n        src=\"/static/fe43118105fcf863b5d7898e9fd17c7e/c0388/pqz7dxg9lg6wa_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/fe43118105fcf863b5d7898e9fd17c7e/772e8/pqz7dxg9lg6wa_small.png 200w,\n/static/fe43118105fcf863b5d7898e9fd17c7e/e17e5/pqz7dxg9lg6wa_small.png 400w,\n/static/fe43118105fcf863b5d7898e9fd17c7e/c0388/pqz7dxg9lg6wa_small.png 542w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 542px) 100vw, 542px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">A set of three playing cards has 48 possible positions when all permutations\nand orientations are considered.</p>\n<h2 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-4xl\">Understanding the Rubik’s Cube</h2>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We now have all the knowledge we need to calculate the total number of\npositions for the Rubik’s Cube. We know that, given a set of <em>n</em> items with <em>p</em>\norientations, the total number of positions for that set of items can be\ncalculated.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 316px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/cef6d9963b674d082fde1a24a679d716/67145/mdvpysojodz6ka_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 34%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"09-equation-total-perms.png\"\n        title=\"09-equation-total-perms.png\"\n        src=\"/static/cef6d9963b674d082fde1a24a679d716/67145/mdvpysojodz6ka_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/cef6d9963b674d082fde1a24a679d716/772e8/mdvpysojodz6ka_small.png 200w,\n/static/cef6d9963b674d082fde1a24a679d716/67145/mdvpysojodz6ka_small.png 316w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 316px) 100vw, 316px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Once we understand how the Rubik’s Cube is built, we can apply this formula and\ncalculate the total number of positions.</p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Anatomy of a Rubik’s Cube</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">The Rubik’s Cube has six sides and each side has nine squares, but this is not\na good way to think about the cube when trying to count the number of\npositions. Instead, we need to understand <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1p0qN1_qWoA\" class=\"text-blue-700\">how the cube is\nbuilt</a>, what types of pieces there\nare, and how each piece moves around the puzzle.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\" style=\"padding-bottom: 56.285714285714285%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden; margin-bottom: 1.0725rem\" > <iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/1p0qN1_qWoA\" class=\"py-4\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen style=\" position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; \"> </iframe> </div>\n<p class=\"py-4\">It’s important to understand that the Rubik’s Cube has <strong>three types of\npieces</strong>. Each behaves differently as we turn the sides of the cube. We’ll keep\nthis in mind as we do our calculations.</p>\n<h2 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-4xl\">Calculating Positions</h2>\n<p class=\"py-4\">The total number of positions for the Rubik’s Cube can be calculated by looking\nat each of the three types of pieces separately.</p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Center Positions</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">There are six center pieces and they are located at the center of each face of\nthe Rubik’s Cube. <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1p0qN1_qWoA\" class=\"text-blue-700\">As we learned</a>,\nthe center pieces are part of a fixed axle that does not move. All the other\npieces move <em>around</em> the center pieces.  This means that the center pieces have\n<strong>one permutation</strong> and <strong>one orientation</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Intuitively we know that something with <em>one</em> permutations and <em>one</em>\norientation has a <strong>single position</strong>, but we can verify by plugging these\nnumbers into our equation.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 488px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3572ea1c880111dbd7c4ca4c47c9019d/bd48c/55tzbpl0cgaauw_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 21.999999999999996%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"11-center-permutations.png\"\n        title=\"11-center-permutations.png\"\n        src=\"/static/3572ea1c880111dbd7c4ca4c47c9019d/bd48c/55tzbpl0cgaauw_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3572ea1c880111dbd7c4ca4c47c9019d/772e8/55tzbpl0cgaauw_small.png 200w,\n/static/3572ea1c880111dbd7c4ca4c47c9019d/e17e5/55tzbpl0cgaauw_small.png 400w,\n/static/3572ea1c880111dbd7c4ca4c47c9019d/bd48c/55tzbpl0cgaauw_small.png 488w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 488px) 100vw, 488px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 640px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/78d5c35c16a1a66695669879aa5ef766/6af66/4j5xjke8vkn0gq_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"12-centers.png\"\n        title=\"12-centers.png\"\n        src=\"/static/78d5c35c16a1a66695669879aa5ef766/6af66/4j5xjke8vkn0gq_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/78d5c35c16a1a66695669879aa5ef766/772e8/4j5xjke8vkn0gq_small.png 200w,\n/static/78d5c35c16a1a66695669879aa5ef766/e17e5/4j5xjke8vkn0gq_small.png 400w,\n/static/78d5c35c16a1a66695669879aa5ef766/6af66/4j5xjke8vkn0gq_small.png 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Corner Positions</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Every three dimensional cube has <strong>eight corners</strong> and the Rubik’s Cube is no\nexception. Unlike the centers, each corner piece can be moved and rotated.\nSince we have eight corners, our total number of permutations for these pieces\nis <strong>eight factorial</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">To figure out the number of orientations for a single piece, we need to count\nthe number of stickers. A corner pieces has three stickers, so it must have\n<strong>three orientations</strong>. As we learned, this means the total number of\norientations for each position of the corners is the <strong>eighth power of three</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">With these numbers, we can calculate the total number of positions for the\ncorner pieces.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 289px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/87735e56e3ab925594f8a6f2c6e21731/c969a/dg15curynbgew_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 37.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"13-corner-perms.png\"\n        title=\"13-corner-perms.png\"\n        src=\"/static/87735e56e3ab925594f8a6f2c6e21731/c969a/dg15curynbgew_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/87735e56e3ab925594f8a6f2c6e21731/772e8/dg15curynbgew_small.png 200w,\n/static/87735e56e3ab925594f8a6f2c6e21731/c969a/dg15curynbgew_small.png 289w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 289px) 100vw, 289px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 640px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/367e6d71e05201df01ce50cc68161d9e/6af66/p458nwmxiyr5w_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"14-corners.png\"\n        title=\"14-corners.png\"\n        src=\"/static/367e6d71e05201df01ce50cc68161d9e/6af66/p458nwmxiyr5w_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/367e6d71e05201df01ce50cc68161d9e/772e8/p458nwmxiyr5w_small.png 200w,\n/static/367e6d71e05201df01ce50cc68161d9e/e17e5/p458nwmxiyr5w_small.png 400w,\n/static/367e6d71e05201df01ce50cc68161d9e/6af66/p458nwmxiyr5w_small.png 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Edge Positions</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">A Rubik’s Cube has <strong>twelve edge pieces</strong> and each piece may be moved or\nflipped.  We can calculate the total number of permutations for these pieces as\n<strong>twelve factorial</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We can use the same method as we did for the corners to determine the number of\norientations for a single edge piece. An edge piece has two stickers, so it\nmust have <strong>two orientations</strong>. This means the total number of orientations for\neach position of the edges is the <strong>twelfth power of two</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\">With these numbers, we can calculate the total number of positions for the edge\npieces.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 379px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/8c8c14198763c0898405ddf18d9e73b6/811d1/myltudgc4d7qfg_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 28.500000000000004%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"15-edge-perms.png\"\n        title=\"15-edge-perms.png\"\n        src=\"/static/8c8c14198763c0898405ddf18d9e73b6/811d1/myltudgc4d7qfg_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8c8c14198763c0898405ddf18d9e73b6/772e8/myltudgc4d7qfg_small.png 200w,\n/static/8c8c14198763c0898405ddf18d9e73b6/811d1/myltudgc4d7qfg_small.png 379w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 379px) 100vw, 379px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 640px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/89bc4999ff43f89cbde342684e5ed19e/6af66/oqgjl53l0tmhsg_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"16-edges.png\"\n        title=\"16-edges.png\"\n        src=\"/static/89bc4999ff43f89cbde342684e5ed19e/6af66/oqgjl53l0tmhsg_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/89bc4999ff43f89cbde342684e5ed19e/772e8/oqgjl53l0tmhsg_small.png 200w,\n/static/89bc4999ff43f89cbde342684e5ed19e/e17e5/oqgjl53l0tmhsg_small.png 400w,\n/static/89bc4999ff43f89cbde342684e5ed19e/6af66/oqgjl53l0tmhsg_small.png 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">Putting It All Together</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We’ve calculated the number of positions for the center pieces, the corner\npieces, and the edge pieces. The final step to finding the total positions for\nthe entire Rubik’s Cube is multiplying these numbers together.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/45f478f080bb34646bafe677901860f4/a6d36/evkjq166zx52ha_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 14.500000000000002%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"17-total-cube-perms.png\"\n        title=\"17-total-cube-perms.png\"\n        src=\"/static/45f478f080bb34646bafe677901860f4/a6d36/evkjq166zx52ha_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/45f478f080bb34646bafe677901860f4/772e8/evkjq166zx52ha_small.png 200w,\n/static/45f478f080bb34646bafe677901860f4/e17e5/evkjq166zx52ha_small.png 400w,\n/static/45f478f080bb34646bafe677901860f4/a6d36/evkjq166zx52ha_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-3xl\">But Wait, There’s More</h3>\n<p class=\"py-4\">We have successfully calculated the number of positions, but we made one fatal\nassumption; our calculations assume that we can take the cube apart. This is\n<em>cheating</em>. Not every position of the Rubik’s Cube is possible if we limit\nourselves to turning the sides.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"p-4 my-4 bg-orange-200 border-l-4 border-orange-500 italic\">\n<p class=\"py-4\">“there is no sequence of moves that will swap a single pair of pieces or\nrotate a single corner or edge cube” - wikipedia</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"py-4\">Because of the limitations of the Rubik’s Cube, only <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubiks_Cube\" class=\"text-blue-700\"><strong>1 in\n12</strong></a> of every position is reachable\nby turning the sides of the cube. We can factor this in to our equation and\nsettle on the total number of <em>legal</em> positions of the Rubik’s Cube.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/5cf5a1c2921214c9ee58a3935bff0f7a/a6d36/c88bk9pt5voctw_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 26%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"18-total-legal-cube-perms.png\"\n        title=\"18-total-legal-cube-perms.png\"\n        src=\"/static/5cf5a1c2921214c9ee58a3935bff0f7a/a6d36/c88bk9pt5voctw_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5cf5a1c2921214c9ee58a3935bff0f7a/772e8/c88bk9pt5voctw_small.png 200w,\n/static/5cf5a1c2921214c9ee58a3935bff0f7a/e17e5/c88bk9pt5voctw_small.png 400w,\n/static/5cf5a1c2921214c9ee58a3935bff0f7a/a6d36/c88bk9pt5voctw_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h2 class=\"font-bold py-4 text-4xl\">How Large Is That?</h2>\n<p class=\"py-4\">There are over 43 quintillion legal positions of the Rubik’s Cube.</p>\n<p class=\"py-4\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/16247ae68f5bf73fb397f5322d6208ac/a6d36/yc2gedgtjumscg_small.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 8%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAACCAIAAADXZGvcAAAACXBIWXMAAAsSAAALEgHS3X78AAAAd0lEQVQI1w2L7QrCIBhGd//3VFhRNnX6YvOL15zLBBss6A4Snh8HznmGGW4zXK2mn7dXjEhG0PKtBuCnMI8l6d+eOT0IeswRFlRyJHq67C2COA9dLwjRT/0QnUArMkLNpq+9XEb13Z5O31OQJT3qajoEw1rxPf4Dv75kgvvFoY0AAAAASUVORK5CYII='); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"19-big-number.png\"\n        title=\"19-big-number.png\"\n        src=\"/static/16247ae68f5bf73fb397f5322d6208ac/a6d36/yc2gedgtjumscg_small.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/16247ae68f5bf73fb397f5322d6208ac/772e8/yc2gedgtjumscg_small.png 200w,\n/static/16247ae68f5bf73fb397f5322d6208ac/e17e5/yc2gedgtjumscg_small.png 400w,\n/static/16247ae68f5bf73fb397f5322d6208ac/a6d36/yc2gedgtjumscg_small.png 650w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<ul class=\"list-disc pl-8 py-4\">\n<li>It would take <strong>thirteen hundred million years</strong> to see every position if you\nwere able to view one thousand per second.</li>\n<li>If we stacked 43 quintillion pennies, the stack would be tall enough to reach\nthe sun and return to the earth over <strong>two hundred and nineteen thousand\ntimes</strong>.</li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":"How Many Positions on a Rubik's Cube?","date":"February 2014","description":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/how-many-positions-on-a-rubiks-cube/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/solving-the-rubiks-cube-in-20-seconds/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Solving The Rubik's Cube in 20 Seconds"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/secrets-of-a-world-memory-champion/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Secrets of a World Memory Champion"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2841359383"]}